Factor analysis of questionnaire ratings


Factor analysis is run on the questionnaire subscales. There are 4 questionnaires: STICSA (2 subscales), TEPS (2 subscales), AMI (3 subscales) and BDI (total score).


library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(psych)
library(ggplot2)
library(corrplot) #plotting correlation matrices
library(GPArotation) #methods for factor rotation
library(nFactors)  #methods for determining the number of factors
library(data.table)
library(brms)


Correlation matrix


# Load data. 
load("All_questionnaires.RData")
quest <- select(All_questionnaires,STICSA_cognitive, STICSA_somatic, TEPS_anticipatory, TEPS_consummatory, AMI_behavioural, AMI_social, AMI_emotional, BDI_score)

# Standardise
quest_standard <- data.frame(scale(quest, center=TRUE, scale=TRUE))
describe(quest_standard)

# Compute correlation matrix between questionnaire subscales
myCormat=mixedCor(data=quest_standard,c=seq(1,ncol(quest_standard),1),smooth=TRUE,global=FALSE)             

# Visualise correlation matrix
corrplot(cor(quest_standard, use="complete.obs"), order = "hclust", tl.col='black', tl.cex=.75)


We can see that the questionnaire subscales are correlated within and between questionnaires.


Determine number of factors


#Parallel analysis: compute number of factors
fa.parallel(myCormat$rho,n.obs=nrow(quest_standard),fm="gls",nfactors=5) # 2 factors

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  2  and the number of components =  2


According to parallel analysis, the questionnaire data is best described using two factors. In the next step, the fatcor loadings are computed.


Run factor analysis


# Run the actual factor analysis:
myFaT=fa(myCormat$rho,nfactors=2,n.obs=nrow(quest_standard),rotate="oblimin",fm="gls")

#----- Plot the results of the factor analysis ------
t1=data.frame(unclass(myFaT$loadings))
ord=colnames(quest_standard) 
t3=data.table(t1,keep.rownames=TRUE)
t3$rn=factor(t3$rn,levels=ord)
t2B=melt.data.table(t3,id.vars="rn",variable.name="factors",value.name="loadings") # could have used 'gather' or 'melt' (from reshape2 or the new pivot_longer from dplyr...)

t2B$factors=recode_factor(t2B$factors,`GLS1`="Anxiety-Depression",`GLS2`="Anhedonia-Apathy") # relabel factors

# Plot factor loadings

plot=ggplot(t2B,aes(rn,(loadings),fill=loadings)) +
  facet_wrap(~ factors, nrow=1) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",aes(fill=abs(loadings)>0.4))+
  scale_fill_manual("legend",values=c("TRUE"="blue","FALSE"="grey"))+
  coord_flip()+
  ylab("Loading strength") +
  theme_minimal(base_size=10)+xlab("")

plot2=plot+
  theme(legend.position="none",axis.text.x=element_text(size=10),axis.text.y=element_text(size=10),text = element_text(size=10),strip.text = element_text(size = 10,face="bold"))+
  ggtitle(" ")
# Print to screen
#
plot2+
  theme(legend.position="none",axis.text.x=element_text(size=10),axis.text.y=element_text(size=10),text = element_text(size=12),strip.text = element_text(size = 10,face="bold"))+
  ggtitle("Exploratory Factor Analysis for mood questionnaires"+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)))


I have labelled the two factors Anxiety-Depression and Anhedonia-Apathy. The subscales of the anxiety (STICSA) and depression questionnaires (BDI) mainly load on the Anxiety-Depression factor, while the subscales from the apathy (AMI) and pleasue questionnaires (TEPS) load on the Anhedonia-Apathy factor.


Factor scores


# Compute factor scores for each person
t2=factor.scores(quest_standard,myFaT)
myScores=data.frame(unclass(t2$scores))
myFactors.scores=myScores
myFactors.scores=dplyr::rename(myFactors.scores,
                                                         AnxietyDepression=GLS1,
                                                         AnhedoniaApathy=GLS2) 
myFactors.scores=cbind(myFactors.scores,All_questionnaires$PROLIFIC_PID) #myDataT$ID)
myFactors.scores=dplyr::rename(myFactors.scores,PROLIFIC_PID=`All_questionnaires$PROLIFIC_PID`)

# Compute factor weighs
factor.weights=as.data.frame(myFaT$weights) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(AnxietyDepression=GLS1,
                AnhedoniaApathy=GLS2)


# Plot factor scores

ggplot(myFactors.scores)+
  geom_point(aes(AnxietyDepression,AnhedoniaApathy), alpha = .6)+
  xlim(-2,2.7)+
  ylim(-2,2.7)

# Compute correlation between fatcor scores
cor.test(myFactors.scores$AnxietyDepression, myFactors.scores$AnhedoniaApathy) # r = 0.288
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  myFactors.scores$AnxietyDepression and myFactors.scores$AnhedoniaApathy
## t = 6.0153, df = 400, p-value = 4.057e-09
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1957249 0.3752547
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.2880185


The factor scores are significantly corrleated (r = 0.288). This is not surprising, given that factor analysis (in contrast to PCA) allows factors to be correlated.
